>>27359435
One of the concepts that I'm thinking over the logistics of is a prompt generator for myself.
Rather than make myself beholden to the thread, borrow an idea from a book that'll be a background element in any upcoming story - randomize things, and stop thinking too hard.
Say I have a few base families that narrow down to genus/species. Add in a rough location and a few other elements. Knock out ~ 500 words Rather than continually knock my head against a wall, train to think quick and see situations in everything.

I had a major idea, and that went well. The next was much slower, and the next more so. I need to practice speed, and not care if the idea stops at 500 words.
Stress will hurt it, like I'm going through now, but that stress can be the best motivation.
It hurts, you'll doubt yourself 2-3x/day at minimum, but when it comes you'll be left wondering how you birthed that.

>>27360106
I find when all else fails simply extrapolate from any media you've already seen.
>I wanna write about [human male] fugging [large] [shy] [snek woman] in the [wild west]
>Why would a human dude be in wild west?
>Cowboy
>Why would a large snake woman be shy in the wild west?
>Well I've always seen cowboy v indian shit
>Large snek is indigenous and lost most of her family to encroaching expansion efforts
>After losing most of her tribe she's had no choice but to integrate with the small growing community
>Oh shit, why would they even end up together though?
>I've seen shows where a wandering cowboy does odd jobs where he travels
>Snek woman is probably poor as fuck, so she does odd jobs
>So they end up working together and establishing a relationship in a small growing community on the frontier

Sprinkle in details like a specific species of snek, a past/more detailed motivation for self-insert anon, and any other personality quirks you feel right about as you develop the foundation further and viola! A mediocre story.

Really just make sure any [important details] are something you're interested in, otherwise ideas won't come.

Anonymous Thu 26 Dec 2019 18:23:34 No.27369419 Report
Quoted By: >>27369516 >>27369547 >>27369782 >>27370282
It's honestly a shame how HFY became a thing on its own. The original idea (which came from that guy who also did that Awful Hospital comic I've seen shilled on this board) was pretty original. Shitloads of science fiction takes humanity as a baseline, making humanity the "jack of all trades" species without anything to define them other than being human. So the entire point was to re-examine that outlook, and the guy gives the example of humanity's niche on Earth. You've heard it by this point, but we're fast long distance runners and have high endurance in general. We're actually pretty large as far as mammals go, particularly for omnivores. Stuff like that.

And then everyone just turned it into "human fite gud" or, worse and edgier, "human genocide gud".

It was supposed to be a thought exercise, not a genre of internet fiction.
